        "text": "### Comparison with the Irving–Williams Series\n\nThe classic **Irving–Williams series** predicts:\n\n> Mn²⁺ < Fe²⁺ < Co²⁺ < Ni²⁺ < **Cu²⁺** > Zn²⁺\n\n| Feature | Irving–Williams prediction | SRD-46 data | Match? |\n|---------|---------------------------|-------------|--------|\n| Mn²⁺ weakest | Lowest of the series | log β₁ = 1.00 (lowest) | ✅ |\n| Co²⁺ < Ni²⁺ | Monotonic increase | 2.11 < 2.80 | ✅ |\n| Cu²⁺ is the maximum | Strongest complex | 4.31 (highest) | ✅ |\n| Cu²⁺ > Zn²⁺ | Drop after Cu | 4.31 > 2.37 | ✅ |\n| Zn²⁺ < Ni²⁺ | Zn falls back below Ni | 2.37 < 2.80 | ✅ |\n\n**Yes — the ammonia log β₁ values follow the Irving–Williams series.** Every testable prediction of the series is confirmed by the SRD-46 data. The characteristic \"hump\" at Cu²⁺ is striking: its log β₁ is nearly **1.5 log units** above the next strongest binder (Ni²⁺) and more than **3 log units** above Mn²⁺. This reflects the Jahn–Teller-enhanced ligand-field stabilisation energy (LFSE) of the d⁹ Cu²⁺ ion, which provides extra thermodynamic driving force for complex formation. The subsequent drop to Zn²⁺ (d¹⁰, zero LFSE) is textbook behaviour — Zn²⁺ relies solely on electrostatic and covalent contributions without any crystal-field bonus.\n\nThe absence of Fe²⁺ data is itself consistent with the series: Fe²⁺–NH₃ binding is expected to be weak (log β₁ somewhere between Mn²⁺ and Co²⁺), and the experimental difficulty of working with air-sensitive Fe²⁺ solutions explains the data gap.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
